did.unittitle: Cross & Brown Company architectural photograph collection
did.abstract: The Cross & Brown Company architectural photograph collection consists of photographs, negatives, slides, pamphlets, correspondence, and other documents describing or depicting buildings in New York City, New York State, and New Jersey, created by the Cross & Brown Company real estate firm.
did.physloc: Materials in this collection may be stored offsite. For more information on making arrangements to consult them, please visit www.nyhistory.org/library/visit.
did.langmaterial: This collection is primarily visual. Any text is likely to be in English.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Materials in this collection may be stored offsite. For more information on making arrangements to consult them, please visit www.nyhistory.org/library/visit.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p:
This collection is organized in four series based on format:
Series I: Photographs
Series II: Negatives
Series III: Slides
Series IV: Documents

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: Cross & Brown Company was a large New York real estate company that had a "total service" approach to the business. Beginning in 1910 as a real estate brokerage, the company expanded throughout the twentieth century into real estate management, appraisals, consultations, industrial surveys, and other special services. Cross & Brown's headquarters was located in Manhattan from its formation until its acquisition by Insignia Douglas Elliman in 1991. The company's final address was 522 Fifth Avenue. Branch offices were located at 63 Wall Street, and in Long Island City, White Plains (New York), Springfield (New Jersey), and Westport (Connecticut). Cross & Brown was also affiliated with real estate companies across the United States and in Canada. In Manhattan, the company predominantly leased commercial and office buildings, while outside the city the firm concentrated on industrial projects and large commercial ventures.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: This collection should be cited as Cross & Brown Company Architectural Photograph Collection, PR 111, Department of Prints, Photographs, and Architectural Collections, The New-York Historical Society.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Materials
relatedmaterial.p: A greater portion of Cross & Brown Company records, including such items as brochures, floor plans, renderings, photographs, and data sheets for specific buildings, are available in the New-York Historical Society Library.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Cross & Brown Company Architectural Photograph Collection spans the period from circa 1970 through 1991 and contains photographs, negatives, slides, and documents relating to the company's real estate business. The collection is divided into four series: Photographs; Negatives; Slides; and Documents.

Materials relate primarily to properties in New York City and State, and primarily depict or otherwise describe large buildings. Attractive architectural views of such recognizable structures as the MetLife Tower, the RCA Building, the Pan Am Building (now the MetLife Building), the World Trade Center, and the Plaza Hotel are included. Materials used by Cross & Brown for the development of brochures and other marketing and promotional tools can be found throughout the collection, from photographs and negatives used for illustrations, to slides and notes for presentations. Materials have been arranged into series based on housing and preservation needs, so researchers should check each series for materials relating to a given property.

userestrict.head: Use Restrictions
userestrict.p: Taking images of documents from the library collections for reference purposes by using hand-held cameras and in accordance with the library's photography guidelines is encouraged. As an alternative, patrons may request up to 20 images per day from staff.

Application to use images from this collection for publication should be made in writing to: Department of Rights and Reproductions, The New-York Historical Society, 170 Central Park West, New York, NY 10024-5194, rightsandrepro@nyhistory.org. Phone: (212) 873-3400 ext. 282.

Copyrights and other proprietary rights may subsist in individuals and entities other than the New-York Historical Society, in which case the patron is responsible for securing permission from those parties. For fuller information about rights and reproductions from N-YHS visit: https://www.nyhistory.org/about/rights-reproductions

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series I is the largest of the series and contains a variety of color and black and white photographs and contact prints. The series is divided into four subseries: Manhattan Properties, New Jersey Properties, New York State Properties, and Cross & Brown Company photographs. Most of these images were used primarily in promotional publications, some of which can be found in Series IV. Most photographs are of building exteriors, but a few interior views are included.

Photographs of Manhattan buildings date from the early 1970s through 1991, and primarily depict large office buildings. Images are arranged alphabetically by named streets, which are followed by numbered avenues and numbered streets; thereunder photographs are arranged by address.
The New Jersey Properties subseries consists of only one property, located in northern Bergen County on Livingston Avenue.

New York State Properties include a variety of sites, mostly commercial or industrial, arranged alphabetically by town. Most are located within a one hundred mile radius of New York City. Properties in the outer boroughs of New York City are included in this subseries, reflecting Cross & Brown's original filing scheme. The largest groupings depict properties in Brooklyn, Queens, and White Plains.

Company photographs date entirely from the 1980s, and include portraits of Cross & Brown Company employees, arranged alphabetically by name, and photographs of company seminars and meetings, arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series II is divided into three subseries: Manhattan Properties, New York State Properties, and Cross & Brown Company photographs. The first two series span the years from the early 1970s until the beginning of the 1990s, while company photographs date exclusively from the 1980s. Manhattan properties are arranged alphabetically by street, followed numerically by numbered avenues and then numbered streets. New York State Properties are arranged alphabetically by town (or borough). As in Series I, buildings in New York City's outer boroughs are filed under New York State. Cross & Brown Company photographs are filed by name of individual or event, as in Series I.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series III consists entirely slides of Manhattan buildings, arranged by address, dating predominantly from the 1980s.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Series IV consists of a variety of documents relating to buildings depicted in Series I through III. Most of the materials were created to be used in conjunction with photographs in Cross & Brown Company's brochures and other promotional materials; both finished and rough copies of these brochures are available in this series. The series is arranged by Manhattan address, with named streets filed alphabetically followed by numbered avenues and numbered streets. A list of exclusive agency listings for 1980, 1984, and 1985 is filed at the end of the series.
